\begin_layout Abstract
\paragraph_spacing double

\change_inserted 0 1271608290
Traditional asset allocation methods for understanding the tradeoff between
 risk and return do not properly reflect real world situations and concerns.
 Recent research has moved away from normality to model returns and variance
 to account for risk by looking at 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fat tail
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distributions and downside risk.
 Other studies have also considered a multiple period framework through
 rebalancing.
 We investigate the use rebalalncing with fat tail distributions and optimizing
 with downside risk as a consideration.
 Our results verify the underperformance of traditional methods in the single
 period framework and also demonstrate the underperformance of traditional
 methods in a multiple period rebalancing framework.
 We further research the tradeoff between variance and downside risk and
 find a greater difference in downside risk performance between the traditional
 framework and our frameworks.
 We use publicly available indices as benchmarks for seven asset classes.
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

