\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double

\change_deleted 0 1271604204
Another problem with the mean-variance optimization framework is that it
 assumes underlying returns are uncorrelated across time (Fisher, 1994).
 This is clearly not the case, as higher returns in one period may lead
 to equally higher returns the next period because of high expectations
 of market trends.
 To correct for this auto-correlation between period-to-period returns and
 to establish the independence of single-period returns, we used the well-known
 Fisher-Geltner-Webb's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unsmoothing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 methodology.
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Variance provides a mathematically simple measure of risk for asset allocation,
 but it is insufficient as a measure of downside risk.
 Variance symmetrically
\change_inserted 0 1271547603

\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted 0 1271547609
clarify what we mean here, not exactly symmetry
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_unchanged
 accounts for both upside risk and downside risk since it is simply a measure
 of the sample’s average squared deviation from the arithmetic mean.
 When investment managers assess risk, they are typically more concerned
 with downside risk or losses and view upside risk (which may be referred
 to as “excess return”) favorably.
 Value-at-risk (VaR) has been incorporated as another risk measure that
 aims to better account for downside risk than variance.
 VaR is the minimum expected loss at a certain confidence level (typically
 5%) and can be calculated
\change_deleted 0 1271566154
 by taking the value of the return at the specified (5%) boundary of
\change_inserted 0 1271566154
from
\change_unchanged
 a probability density function (PDF) of return data (either historical
 or simulated).
 
\change_deleted 0 1271547619
Although
\change_inserted 0 1271547619
However,
\change_unchanged
 VaR 
\change_deleted 0 1271547628
better accounts for downside risk than variance does, it
\change_unchanged
 fails to capture the extent of the possible losses beyond the specified
 (5%) cutoff.
 It is possible to have two PDF’s with the same VaR (loss associated with
 the cutoff of 5%) but one with a fatter tail and greater losses to the
 left of the specified (5%) cutoff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Conditional value-at-risk (CVaR) attempts to rectify this problem: 
