\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
t-Copula degrees of freedom: 25.25
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The degrees of freedom signifies the extent of the fat tails.
 A degree of freedom of infinite is essentially a normal distribution; previous
 literature have found t-copulas with a degree of freedom of 32 to be a
 very close approximation of a normal copula.
\change_inserted 0 1271604506

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing double
Methodology
\change_inserted 0 1271603780
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Methodology"

\end_inset


\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Arithmetic and 
\change_deleted 0 1271605921
Compounding
\change_inserted 0 1271605922
Geometric
\change_unchanged
 Returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We use two methods for calculating returns for a given time period.
 In the arithmetic approach, returns from a period are added to returns
 in the next period.
 In the 
\change_deleted 0 1271605940
compounding
\change_inserted 0 1271605941
geometric returns
\change_unchanged
 approach, returns from a period are multiplied to the returns in the next
 period.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 be the return during period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 be the portfolio value at the end of period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we can express the two approaches as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Geometric: }V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Arithmetic: }V_{t+1}=V_{t}+r_{r+1}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The use of arithmetic returns is mathematically and computationally convenient.
 Our initial analyses utilize arithmetic returns before extending the mean-CVaR
 framework to consider 
\change_deleted 0 1271605930
compounding
\change_inserted 0 1271605932
geometric returns
\change_unchanged
 and rebalancing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
In order to calculate the CVaR of a certain portfolio over a set of simulations,
 we sort the average returns of all the simulations from lowest to highest
 and take the average of the lowest 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
beta * Number of Simulation$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\beta\text{-CVaR}=\frac{{1}}{(\beta\cdot n)}\sum_{i=1}^{\beta\cdot n}r_{i}\label{eq:CVaR calculation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the number of simulations, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the i-th lowest simulated return of an asset class, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
beta$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the desired CVaR level (expressed as a percentage, e.g.
 5%).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Analytical Mean-Variance Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double

\change_deleted 0 1271569298
Markowitz (1952) pioneered the use of the normal mean-variance optimization
 framework for maximizing portfolio returns and minimizing portfolio risk
 (standard deviation).

\change_unchanged
 Th
\change_inserted 0 1271569301
e
\change_deleted 0 1271569301
is
\change_unchanged
 
\change_inserted 0 1271569308
Markowitz (1952) 
\change_unchanged
framework analytically calculates the optimal set of portfolio returns and
 variances using the historical average return and historical standard deviation
 of each asset class along with the historical covariance between each pair
 of asset classes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the fixed portfolio monthly return rate and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$r_i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the average historical monthly return of each asset class.
 The optimization problem can be expressed as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{\sigma^{2}}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma^{2}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}^{2}\cdot\sigma_{i}^{2}+2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j>i}^{n}w_{i}\cdot w_{j}\cdot\text{Cov(}i,j\text{) }\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Cov(}i,j\text{)}=\sigma_{i}\cdot\sigma_{j}\cdot\rho_{ij}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}\cdot r_{i}=R\end{equation}

\end_inset

The optimization uses multiple levels of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 between the lowest and highest single asset class return (where the portfolio
 is 100% weighted in that single asset class) to determine the set of portfolios
 along the efficient frontier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Single Period Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The single period optimization of mean-CVaR minimizes CVaR at each given
 level of return.
 The optimization calculates the CVaR as described in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CVaR calculation"

\end_inset

 while satisfying the condition that the average return across all simulations
 is equal to the given level of return we are optimizing on.
 Since this is a single period optimization, arithmetic returns are used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the weight for asset class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the fixed portfolio monthly return rate as defined before and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fix this to be consistent with the formula 
\end_layout

\end_inset

be the calculated portfolio monthly return rate at each run of the simulation.
 We have the following optimization problem: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=R(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{t}=V_{t}+\sum_{i=1}^{t}r_{i}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
explain V, what is this variable? delete it since this is single period?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Our two linear constraints indicate that the weights must sum to one and
 be nonnegative (since no borrowing is allowed).
 Since we want to optimize on a fixed return, our nonlinear constraint is
 that our average final portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 across all simulations must be equivalent to the given fixed portfolio
 return 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with 
\change_inserted 0 1271606746
geometric
\change_deleted 0 1271606746
Compounding
\change_unchanged
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Simulated-Mean-CVaR-Optimization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We adopt the 
\change_inserted 0 1271606746
geometric
\change_deleted 0 1271606746
compounding
\change_unchanged
 approach in this optimization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=R(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Our two linear constraints indicate that the weights must sum to one and
 be nonnegative (since no borrowing is allowed).
 Since we want to fix return, our nonlinear constraint is that our final
 portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 must be the same as the given fixed portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with Rebalancing and 
\change_inserted 0 1271606747
geometric
\change_deleted 0 1271606747
Compounding
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The implementation is the same as in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Simulated-Mean-CVaR-Optimization"

\end_inset

 with one additional feature: every 12 months, we rebalance the portfolio
 to the predetermined weights.
 We sum up the returns in that year and we distribute the portfolio value
 according to a predetermined set of weights and then compound it with future
 returns.
 Keeping all the variables the same, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
grammar, this is not a complete sentence
\end_layout

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{{V}_{t}^{'}}$
\end_inset

 be the portfolio vector after rebalancing.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{{V}_{t}^{'}}$
\end_inset

 contains the value of each asset class at the end of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 We have the following nonlinear programming optimization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=R(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\vec{{V}_{t}^{'}}=V_{t}\cdot(w_{1},w_{2},..,w_{n})\label{eq:constraint}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
where the only addition is equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint"

\end_inset

.
 It specifies that at each time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we redistribute the value of the portfolio according to a predetermined
 vector of weights to obtain a portfolio vector containing the values of
 each asset class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Our objective function is to find the weights that will minimize CVaR.
 CVaR is calculated analytically
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
empirical? this is not analytical???
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by trying out a set of asset weights for all 5000
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
#?
\end_layout

\end_inset

 simulations.
 Each simulation gives a final portfolio value, from which we can derive
 the monthly return rate by the formula: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r=\frac{{V_{f}^{1/p}-1}}{b}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the monthly return rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the final portfolio value, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the number of periods we simulate into the future, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is number of months in between which we rebalance.
 A period is the interval in which we rebalance once; it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 months.
 For instance, suppose we start with a $1 billion endowment and the final
 portfolio value is $24.62 billion.
 Suppose further that we simulate 36 months into the future, rebalancing
 every 12 months.
 Then our monthly return rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{24.62^{1/3}-1}{12}=0.16$
\end_inset

 monthly return rate by the formula.
 For each set of weights, we carry out 5000 simulations, giving us 5000
 monthly return rates
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
change the # of simulations, can we have a variable so it is consistent
 throughout the paper? like a cross reference
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We take the average of the lowest 5%, or 250 final returns, to give us
 one CVaR.
 Our objective is to find the minimum CVaR.
 We 
\change_deleted 0 1271569349
will keep trying 
\change_inserted 0 1271569351
repeatedly test 
\change_unchanged
weights in an analytical
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
