\end_layout

\end_inset

 fashion until we find the minimum CVaR.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing double
Results and Discussion
\change_inserted 0 1271602043

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Results-and-Discussion"

\end_inset


\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Efficient Frontiers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Analytical Mean-Variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We created analytical mean-variance efficient frontiers using the average
 returns and observed variances of the historical data, the unsmoothed historica
l data, and the simulation data.
 The similarity of the three efficient frontiers 
\change_inserted 0 1271606030
reflects
\change_deleted 0 1271606034
is a result of 
\change_inserted 0 1271606034
 
\change_unchanged
the similarity of the 
\change_deleted 0 1271606039
mean
\change_inserted 0 1271606042
average returns
\change_unchanged
 and variance
\change_inserted 0 1271606052
s
\change_deleted 0 1271606049
 statistics
\change_unchanged
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Single Period (buy and hold) Mean-CVaR 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We first used the resulting weights of the analytical, normal mean-variance
 efficient frontiers to find their corresponding portfolio CVaR's given
 the simulation data.
 We used this as a comparison to the actual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 set of portfolios in a mean-CVaR framework.
 The
\change_inserted 0 1271606582
 resulting
\change_unchanged
 efficient frontiers 
\change_deleted 0 1271606591
are as follows
\change_inserted 0 1271606603
are shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meancvar_Single-Per-Arith"

\end_inset

.
\change_deleted 0 1271606576
: 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The results indicate that there exists a set of portfolios that has a lower
 CVaR (or higher return) than any of the analytical mean-variance portfolios.
 This is intuitively captured by the fact that optimal mean-CVaR frontier
 lies to the upper left.
 The portfolios that had maximized return and minimized variance in the
 previous optimization had a greater CVaR than portfolios that had minimized
 CVaR.
 This suggests the mean-variance optimization does not protect against situation
s of extreme losses and should not be the only consideration in asset allocation
 especially if preventing extreme downside risk is a central concern.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The convergence of the efficient frontiers at the end points is due to the
 fact that only a portfolio that is 100% weighted in a single asset class
 can achieve the lowest possible return and the highest possible return.
 The outperformance of the optimal mean-CVaR efficient frontier in comparison
 to the mean-variance efficent frontier can be seen in the portfolios between
 the two endpoints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Unlike the analytical mean-variance framework, the mean-CVaR framework allows
 for the risk value to be negative.
 A CVaR less than zero means that the worst 5% performance is a negative
 loss or a small gain.
 It is difficult to use an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

information ratio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sharpe ratio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since the intersection of the efficient frontier and the y-axis leads to
 arbitrarily large ratios.
 It is interesting to note that for an expected loss of 0%, the optimal
 mean-CVaR portfolio will return almost 35 basis points more than the mean-varia
nce portfolio.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Single Period Arithmetic Mean-CVaR
\change_inserted 0 1271606084

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:meancvar_Single-Per-Arith"

\end_inset


\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

